r persistent return and affective bond to ancient Greek logos, mythos, and tragedy sheds light on some of the most complex epistemological issues in contemporary theory, such as the workings of criticism, the language of politics and the politics of language, the possibility of social and symbolic transformation, the multiple mediations between metropolitan and postcolonial contexts of theory and practice, the question of the other, and the function of the feminine in Western metaphysics. With a foreword by Gayatri Chakravorty Spivak and a chapter by Irigaray responding to her commentators, this book is an essential text for those in social theory, comparative literature, or classics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aFeminist theory. 0aPhilosophy, Ancient. 4aGender and Sexuality : Feminist. 4aGender and Sexuality : Gender Studies. 4aLiterature : Literature. 4aPhilosophy : Ancient Greek Philosophy. 4aPhilosophy : Continental Philosophy. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Feminist.2bisacsh1 aAthanasiou, Athena, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAthanasiou, Athena, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBerger, Anne-Emmanuelle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChanter, Tina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChisholm, Dianne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aColebrook, Claire, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDeutscher, Penelope, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGourgouris, Stathis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarrington, Laine M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHuffer, Lynne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/